# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: nixos
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] In computer science, **declarative programming** is a programming paradigm that expresses the logic of a computation without fully describing its control flow.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] This is in contrast with imperative programming, which implements algorithms in explicit steps.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Declarative programming may consider programs as theories of a formal logic, and computations as deductions in that logical theory.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Declarative programming at times simplifies the writing of parallel programs.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Common declarative language paradigms include logic programming (e.g., Prolog, Datalog, answer set programming), and algebraic modeling systems.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is often defined as any style of programming that is not imperative.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] A number of other common definitions attempt to define it by simply contrasting it with imperative programming.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] These definitions overlap substantially.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is a non-imperative style of programming in which programs describe their desired results without explicitly listing commands or steps that must be performed.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages are characterized by a mostly declarative programming style.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] In logic programming, programs consist of sentences expressed in logical form, and computation uses those sentences to solve problems, which are also expressed in logical form.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] In a pure functional language, such as Haskell, all functions are without side effects, and state changes are only represented as functions that transform the state, which is explicitly represented as a first-class object in the program.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Although pure functional languages are non-imperative, they often provide a facility for describing the effect of a function as a series of steps.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Other functional languages, such as Lisp, OCaml and Erlang, support a mixture of procedural and functional programming.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Some logic programming languages, such as Prolog, and database query languages, such as SQL, while declarative in principle, also support a procedural style of programming.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is an umbrella term that includes a number of better-known programming paradigms.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Constraint programming states relations between variables in the form of constraints that specify the properties of the target solution.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] The set of constraints is solved by giving a value to each variable so that the solution is consistent with the maximum number of constraints.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Constraint programming often complements other paradigms: functional, logical, or even imperative programming.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Makefiles, for example, specify dependencies in a declarative fashion, but include an imperative list of actions to take as well.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Similarly, yacc specifies a context free grammar declaratively, but includes code snippets from a host language, which is usually imperative (such as C).
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages, such as Prolog, Datalog and answer set programming, compute by proving that a goal is a logical consequence of the program, or by showing that the goal is true in a model defined by the program.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Prolog computes by reducing goals to subgoals, top-down using backward reasoning, whereas most Datalog systems compute bottom-up using forward reasoning.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Answer set programs typically use SAT solvers to generate a model of the program.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Models, or mathematical representations, of physical systems may be implemented in computer code that is declarative.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] The code contains a number of equations, not imperative assignments, that describe ("declare") the behavioral relationships.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] When a model is expressed in this formalism, a computer is able to perform algebraic manipulations to best formulate the solution algorithm.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] The mathematical causality is typically imposed at the boundaries of the physical system, while the behavioral description of the system itself is declarative or acausal.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Declarative modeling languages and environments include Analytica, Modelica and Simile.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Prolog (1972) stands for "PROgramming in LOGic." It was developed for natural language question answering, using SL resolution both to deduce answers to queries and to parse and generate natural language sentences.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] The building blocks of a Prolog program are *facts* and *rules*.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Given this program, the query `eat(tom,jerry)` succeeds, while `eat(jerry,tom)` fails.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Moreover, the query `eat(X,jerry)` succeeds with the answer substitution `X=tom`.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Prolog executes programs top-down, using SLD resolution to reason backwards, reducing goals to subgoals.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] In this example, it uses the last rule of the program to reduce the goal of answering the query `eat(X,jerry)` to the subgoals of first finding an X such that `big(X)` holds and then of showing that `small(jerry)` holds.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] It repeatedly uses rules to further reduce subgoals to other subgoals, until it eventually succeeds in unifying all subgoals with facts in the program.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] This backward reasoning, goal-reduction strategy treats rules in logic programs as procedures, and makes Prolog both a declarative and procedural programming language.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] The broad range of Prolog applications is highlighted in the Year of Prolog Book, celebrating the 50 year anniversary of Prolog.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] The origins of Datalog date back to the beginning of logic programming, but it was identified as a separate area around 1977.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Syntactically and semantically, it is a subset of Prolog.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] But because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Most Datalog systems execute programs bottom-up, using rules to reason forwards, deriving new facts from existing facts, and terminating when there are no new facts that can be derived, or when the derived facts unify with the query.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Datalog has been applied to such problems as data integration, information extraction, networking, security, cloud computing and machine learning.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Answer set programming (ASP) evolved in the late 1990s, based on the stable model (answer set) semantics of logic programming.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Like Datalog, it is a subset of Prolog; and, because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Most implementations of ASP execute a program by first *grounding* the program, replacing all variables in rules by constants in all possible ways, and then using a propositional SAT solver, such as the DPLL algorithm to generate one or more models of the program.
[src:nixos/declarative-programming] Its applications are oriented towards solving difficult search problems and knowledge representation.
[src:nixos/download] We recommend the multi-user install if you are on Linux running systemd, with SELinux disabled and you can authenticate with `sudo`.
[src:nixos/download] Above command will perform a single-user installation of Nix, meaning that `nix` is owned by the invoking user.
[src:nixos/download] You should run this under your usual user account, not as `root`.
[src:nixos/download] The script will invoke `sudo` to create `/nix` if it doesn’t already exist.
[src:nixos/download] Install Nix via the **recommended** multi-user installation.
[src:nixos/download] We believe we have ironed out how to cleanly support the read-only root on modern macOS.
[src:nixos/download] Please consult the manual on details what the installation script does.
[src:nixos/download] WSL versions 0.67.6 and above has systemd support.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] A **Linux distribution**, often abbreviated as **distro**, is an operating system that includes the Linux kernel for its kernel functionality.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Although the name does not imply product distribution per se, a distro—if distributed on its own—is often obtained via a website intended specifically for the purpose.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Distros have been designed for a wide variety of systems ranging from personal computers (for example, Linux Mint and Zorin OS) to servers (for example, Red Hat Enterprise Linux) and from embedded devices (for example, OpenWrt) to supercomputers (for example, Rocks Cluster Distribution).
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] A distro typically includes many components in addition to the Linux kernel.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Commonly, it includes a package manager, an init system (such as systemd, OpenRC, SysVinit, or runit), GNU tools and libraries, documentation, IP network configuration utilities, the getty TTY setup program, and many more.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Typically, most of the included software is free and open-source software – made available both as binary for convenience and as source code to allow for modifying it.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] A distro may also include proprietary software that is not available in source code form, such as a device driver binary.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] A distro may be described as a particular assortment of application and utility software (various GNU tools and libraries, for example), packaged with the Linux kernel in such a way that its capabilities meet users' needs.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] The software is usually adapted to the distribution and then combined into software packages by the distribution's maintainers.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] The software packages are available online in repositories, which are storage locations usually distributed around the world.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Beside "glue" components, such as the distribution installers (for example, Debian-Installer and Anaconda) and the package management systems, very few packages are actually written by a distribution's maintainers.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Distributions have been designed for a wide range of computing environments, including desktops, servers, laptops, netbooks, mobile devices (phones and tablets), and embedded systems.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] There are commercially backed distributions, such as Red Hat Enterprise Linux (Red Hat), openSUSE (SUSE) and Ubuntu (Canonical), and entirely community-driven distributions, such as Debian, Slackware, Gentoo and Arch Linux.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Most distributions come ready-to-use and prebuilt for a specific instruction set, while some (such as Gentoo) are distributed mostly in source code form and must be built before installation.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Linus Torvalds developed the Linux kernel and distributed its first version, 0.01, in 1991.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Linux was initially distributed as source code only, and later as a pair of downloadable floppy disk images: one bootable and containing the Linux kernel itself, and the other with a set of GNU utilities and tools for setting up a file system.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Since the installation procedure was complicated, especially in the face of growing amounts of available software, distributions sprang up to simplify it.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] The two oldest, still active distribution projects started in 1993.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] The SLS distribution was not well maintained, so in July 1993 a new SLS-based distribution, Slackware, was released by Patrick Volkerding.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Also dissatisfied with SLS, Ian Murdock set to create a free distribution by founding Debian in August 1993, with first public BETA released in January 1994 and first stable version in June 1996.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Users were attracted to Linux distributions as alternatives to MS-DOS compatible operating systems, Windows, Classic Mac OS, and proprietary versions of Unix.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Most early adopters were familiar with Unix from work or school.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] They embraced Linux distributions for their low (or absent) cost, and the availability of the source code for most or all of their software.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] As of 2025, Linux has become more popular in server and embedded devices markets than in the desktop market.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] It is used in approximately 64.5% of web servers; its current operating system market share is about 2.51%, and its desktop operating system market share is about 2.94%.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Many Linux distributions provide an installation system akin to that provided with other modern operating systems.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Other distributions, including Gentoo Linux, provide only the binaries of a basic kernel, compilation tools, and an installer; the installer compiles all the requested software for the specific architecture of the user's computer, using these tools and the software's source code.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Distributions are normally segmented into *packages*.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Each package contains a specific application or service.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Examples of packages are a library for handling the PNG image format, a collection of fonts, and a web browser.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] The package is typically provided as compiled code, with installation and removal of packages handled by a package management system (PMS) rather than a simple file archiver.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Each package intended for such a PMS contains meta-information such as its description, version number, and its dependencies (other packages it requires to run).
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] The package management system evaluates this meta-information to allow package searches, perform automatic upgrades to newer versions, and to check that all dependencies of a package are present (and either notify the user to install them, or install them automatically).
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] The package can also be provided as source code to be compiled on the system.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Most distributions install packages, including the kernel and other core operating system components, in a predetermined configuration.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] A few now require or permit configuration adjustments at first install time.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] This makes installation less daunting, particularly for new users, but is not always acceptable.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] For specific requirements, much software must be carefully configured to be useful, to work correctly with other software, or to be secure, and local administrators are often obliged to spend time reviewing and reconfiguring it.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Some (but not all) distributions go to considerable lengths to adjust and customize the software they include, and some provide configuration tools to help users do so.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] By obtaining and installing *everything* normally provided in a distribution, an administrator may create a "distribution less" installation.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] It is possible to build such systems from scratch, avoiding distributions altogether.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] One needs a way to generate the first binaries until the system is *self-hosting*.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] This can be done via compilation on another system capable of building binaries for the intended target (possibly by cross-compilation).
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] The diversity of Linux distributions is due to technical, organizational, and philosophical variation among vendors and users.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] The permissive licensing of free software means that users with sufficient knowledge and interest can customize any extant distribution, or design one to suit their own needs.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Rolling Linux distributions are kept current using small and frequent updates.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] The terms *partially rolling* and *partly rolling* (along with synonyms *semi-rolling* and *half-rolling*), *fully rolling*, *truly rolling* and *optionally rolling* are sometimes used by software developers and users.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Repositories of **rolling distributions** usually contain very recent software releases—often the latest stable versions available.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] They have pseudo-releases and installation media that are simply snapshots of the distribution at the time of the installation image's release.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Typically, a rolling-release OS installed from older installation medium can be fully updated after it is installed.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Depending on the usage case, there can be pros and cons to both standard release and rolling release software development methodologies.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] In terms of the software development process, **standard releases** require significant development effort to keep old versions up-to-date by propagating bug fixes back to the newest branch, versus focusing on the newest development branch.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Also, unlike rolling releases, standard releases require more than one code branch to be developed and maintained, which increases the workload of the software developers and maintainers.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] On the other hand, software features and technology planning are easier in standard releases due to a better understanding of upcoming features in the next version(s).
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Software release cycles can also be synchronized with those of major upstream software projects, such as desktop environments.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] As for the user experience, standard releases are often viewed as more stable and bug-free since software conflicts can be more easily addressed and the software stack more thoroughly tested and evaluated, during the software development cycle.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] For this reason, they tend to be the preferred choice in enterprise environments and mission-critical tasks.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] However, rolling releases offer more current software which can also provide increased stability and fewer software bugs along with the additional benefits of new features, greater functionality, faster running speeds, and improved system and application security.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Regarding software security, the rolling release model can have advantages in timely security updates, fixing system or application security bugs and vulnerabilities, that standard releases may have to wait till the next release for or patch in various versions.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] In a rolling release distribution, where the user has chosen to run it as a highly dynamic system, the constant flux of software packages can introduce new unintended vulnerabilities.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] A "live" distribution is a Linux distribution that can be booted from removable storage media such as optical discs or USB flash drives, instead of being installed on and booted from a hard disk drive.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] The portability of installation-free distributions makes them advantageous for applications such as demonstrations, borrowing someone else's computer, rescue operations, or as installation media for a standard distribution.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] When the operating system is booted from a read-only medium such as a CD or DVD, any user data that needs to be retained between sessions cannot be stored on the boot device but must be written to another storage device, such as a USB flash drive or a hard disk drive.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Many Linux distributions provide a "live" form in addition to their conventional form, which is a network-based or removable-media image intended to be used only for installation; such distributions include antiX, SUSE, Ubuntu, Linux Mint, MX Linux and Fedora Linux.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Some distributions, including Knoppix, Puppy Linux, Devil-Linux, SuperGamer, SliTaz GNU/Linux and dyne:bolic, are designed primarily for live use.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Additionally, some minimal distributions can be run directly from as little space as one floppy disk without the need to change the contents of the system's hard disk drive.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] The website DistroWatch lists many Linux distributions and displays some of the ones that have the most web traffic on the site.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] The Wikimedia Foundation released an analysis of the browser User Agents of visitors to WMF websites until 2015, which includes details of the most popular Operating System identifiers, including some Linux distributions.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Many of the popular distributions are listed below.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Whether such operating systems count as a "Linux distribution" is a controversial topic.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] They use the Linux kernel, so the Linux Foundation and Chris DiBona, Google's former open-source chief, agree that Android is a Linux distribution; others, such as Google engineer Patrick Brady, disagree by noting the lack of support for many GNU tools in Android, including glibc.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Other Linux-kernel-based operating systems include Tizen, Mer/Sailfish OS, KaiOS and Amazon's Kindle firmware.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Lightweight Linux distributions are those that have been designed with support for older hardware in mind, allowing older hardware to still be used productively, or, for maximum possible speed in newer hardware by leaving more resources available for use by applications.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Examples include antiX, Damn Small Linux (based on antiX), Tiny Core Linux, Puppy Linux and Slitaz.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] The Free Standards Group was an organization formed by major software and hardware vendors that aims to improve interoperability between different distributions.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Among their proposed standards are the Linux Standard Base, which defines a common ABI and packaging system for Linux, and the Filesystem Hierarchy Standard which recommends a standard file naming chart, notably the basic directory names found on the root of the tree of any Linux filesystem.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Those standards, however, see limited use, even among the distributions developed by members of the organization.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] The diversity of Linux distributions means that not all software runs on all distributions, depending on what libraries and other system attributes are required.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Packaged software and software repositories are usually specific to a particular distribution, though cross-installation is sometimes possible on closely related distributions.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] One of solutions for interdistribution issues, particularly to run software created for a distribution on another, is by using container such as Distrobox.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] There are several ways to install a Linux distribution.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] The most popular method of installing Linux is by booting from a live USB memory stick, which can be created by using a USB image writer application and the ISO image, which can be downloaded from various Linux distribution websites.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] DVD disks, CD disks, network installations and even other hard drives can also be used as "installation media".
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] In the 1990s, Linux distributions were installed using sets of floppy disks, but this has been abandoned by all major distributions.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] By the 2000s, many distributions offered CD and DVD sets with the vital packages on the first disk and less important packages on later ones.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Some distributions, such as Debian also enabled installing over a network after booting from either a set of floppy disks or a CD with only a small amount of data on it.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] New users tend to begin by partitioning a hard drive to keep their formerly installed operating system.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] The Linux distribution can then be installed on its own separate partition without affecting formerly saved data.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] In a Live CD setup, the computer boots the entire operating system from CD without first installing it on the computer's hard disk.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Many distributions have a Live CD *installer*, where the computer boots the operating system from the disk, and it can then be installed on the computer's hard disk, providing a seamless transition from the OS running from the CD to the OS running from the hard disk.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Both servers and personal computers that come with Linux already installed are available from vendors including Hewlett-Packard, Dell and System76.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] On embedded devices, Linux is typically held in the device's firmware and may or may not be consumer-accessible.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Anaconda, one of the more popular installers, is used by Red Hat Enterprise Linux, Fedora (which uses the Fedora Media Writer) and other distributions to simplify the installation process.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Debian, Ubuntu and many others use Debian-Installer.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] The process of constantly switching between distributions is often referred to as "distro hopping".
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Virtual machine software such as VirtualBox and VMware Workstation virtualize hardware allowing users to test live media on a virtual machine without installing to the real system.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Some websites like DistroWatch offer lists of distributions, and link to screenshots of operating systems as a way to get a first impression of various distributions.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Some distributions let the user install Linux on top of their current system, such as coLinux.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Linux is installed to the Windows hard disk partition, and can be started from inside Windows itself.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Virtual machines (such as VirtualBox or VMware Workstation) also make it possible for Linux to be run inside another OS.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] The VM software simulates a separate computer onto which the Linux system is installed.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] After installation, the virtual machine can be booted as if it were an independent computer.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Some specific proprietary software products are not available in any form for Linux.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] As of September 2015, the Steam gaming service has over 1,500 games available on Linux, compared to 2,323 games for Mac and 6,500 Windows games.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Emulation and API-translation projects like Wine and CrossOver make it possible to run non-Linux-based software on Linux systems, either by emulating a proprietary operating system or by translating proprietary API calls (e.g., calls to Microsoft's Win32 or DirectX APIs) into native Linux API calls.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] A virtual machine can also be used to run a proprietary OS (like Microsoft Windows) on top of Linux.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Pre-built computers are usually sold with an operating system other than Linux already installed by the original equipment manufacturer (OEM).
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] This limits Linux's market share: consumers are unaware that an alternative exists, they must make a conscious effort to use a different operating system, and they must either perform the actual installation themselves, or depend on support from a friend, relative, or computer professional.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] However, it is possible to buy hardware with Linux already installed.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Lenovo, Hewlett-Packard, Dell, Affordy, Purism, Pine64 and System76 all sell general-purpose Linux laptops.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Custom-order PC manufacturers will also build Linux systems, but possibly with the Windows key on the keyboard.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Fixstars Solutions (formerly Terra Soft) sold Macintosh computers and PlayStation 3 consoles with Yellow Dog Linux installed.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] It is more common to find embedded devices sold with Linux as the default manufacturer-supported OS, including the Linksys NSLU2 NAS device, TiVo's line of personal video recorders, and Linux-based cellphones (including Android smartphones), PDAs, and portable music players.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] The current Microsoft Windows license lets the manufacturer determine the refund policy.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] With prior versions of Windows, it was possible to obtain a refund if the manufacturer failed to provide the refund by litigation in the small claims courts.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] On February 15, 1999, a group of Linux users in Orange County, California held a "Windows Refund Day" protest in an attempt to pressure Microsoft into issuing them refunds.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] There are no official figures on the popularity, adoption, downloads or installed base of Linux distributions.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] There are also no official figures for the total number of Linux systems, partly due to the difficulty of quantifying the number of PCs running Linux (see Desktop Linux adoption), since many users download Linux distributions.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Hence, the sales figures for Linux systems and commercial Linux distributions indicate a much lower number of Linux systems and level of Linux adoption than is the case; this is mainly due to Linux being free and open-source software that can be downloaded free of charge.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] A Linux Counter Project had kept track of a running guesstimate of the number of Linux systems, but did not distinguish between rolling release and standard release distributions.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] It ceased operation in August 2018, though a few related blog posts were created through October 2018.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Desktop usage statistical reports for particular Linux distributions have been collected and published since July 2014 by the Linux Hardware Project.
[src:nixos/linux-distribution] Statcounter, a web traffic analysis company, within the *operating system market share*, showed that the Linux operating systems had, according to them, 3.9% of the worldwide market share in July 2025.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] This manual describes how to install, use and extend NixOS, a Linux distribution based on the purely functional package management system Nix, that is composed using modules and packages defined in the Nixpkgs project.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Additional information regarding the Nix package manager and the Nixpkgs project can be found in respectively the Nix manual and the Nixpkgs manual.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] If you encounter problems, please report them on the `Discourse`, the Matrix room, or on the `#nixos` channel on Libera.Chat.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Alternatively, consider contributing to this manual.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Bugs should be reported in NixOS’ GitHub issue tracker.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Commands prefixed with `#` have to be run as root, either requiring to login as root user or temporarily switching to it using `sudo` for example.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] This section describes how to obtain, install, and configure NixOS for first-time use.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] NixOS ISO images can be downloaded from the NixOS download page.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Follow the instructions in the section called “Booting from a USB flash drive” to create a bootable USB flash drive.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] If you have a very old system that can’t boot from USB, you can burn the image to an empty CD.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] NixOS might not work very well on such systems.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] To begin the installation, you have to boot your computer from the install drive.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Open the boot menu by pressing the appropriate key, which is usually shown on the display on early boot.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Select the USB flash drive (the option usually contains the word “USB”).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] If you choose the incorrect drive, your computer will likely continue to boot as normal.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] In that case restart your computer and pick a different drive.NoteThe key to open the boot menu is different across computer brands and even models.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] If you are unsure and don’t see it on the early boot screen, you can search online for your computers brand, model followed by “boot from usb”.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] The computer might not even have that feature, so you have to go into the BIOS/UEFI settings to change the boot order.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Again, search online for details about your specific computer model.For Apple computers with Intel processors press and hold the **⌥** (Option or Alt) key until you see the boot menu.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] On Apple silicon press and hold the power button.NoteIf your computer supports both BIOS and UEFI boot, choose the UEFI option.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] You will likely need to disable “Secure Boot” to use the UEFI option.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] The exact steps vary by device manufacturer but generally “Secure Boot” will be listed under “Boot”, “Security” or “Advanced” in the BIOS/UEFI menu.NoteIf you use a CD for the installation, the computer will probably boot from it automatically.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] If not, choose the option containing the word “CD” from the boot menu.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Shortly after selecting the appropriate boot drive, you should be presented with a menu with different installer options.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Leave the default and wait (or press **Enter** to speed up).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] The graphical images will start their corresponding desktop environment and the graphical installer, which can take some time.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] The minimal images will boot to a command line.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] You have to follow the instructions in the section called “Manual Installation” there.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] The graphical installer is recommended for desktop users and will guide you through the installation.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Next you should choose your location to have the timezone set correctly.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] You can actually click on the map!NoteThe installer will use an online service to guess your location based on your public IP address.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Then you can select the keyboard layout.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] The default keyboard model should work well with most desktop keyboards.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] If you have a special keyboard or notebook, your model might be in the list.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Select the language you are most comfortable typing in.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] On the “Users” screen, you have to type in your display name, login name and password.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] You can also enable an option to automatically login to the desktop.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Then you have the option to choose a desktop environment.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] If you want to create a custom setup with a window manager, you can select “No desktop”.TipIf you don’t have a favorite desktop and don’t know which one to choose, you can stick to either GNOME or Plasma.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] They have a quite different design, so you should choose whichever you like better.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] They are both popular choices and well tested on NixOS.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] You have the option to allow unfree software in the next screen.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] The easiest option in the “Partitioning” screen is “Erase disk”, which will delete all data from the selected disk and install the system on it.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Also select “Swap (with Hibernation)” in the dropdown below it.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] You have the option to encrypt the whole disk with LUKS.NoteAt the top left you see if the Installer was booted with BIOS or UEFI.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] If you know your system supports UEFI and it shows “BIOS”, reboot with the correct option.WarningMake sure you have selected the correct disk at the top and that no valuable data is still on the disk!
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] It will be deleted when formatting the disk.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Check the choices you made in the “Summary” and click “Install”.NoteThe installation takes about 15 minutes.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] The time varies based on the selected desktop environment, internet connection speed and disk write speed.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] When the install is complete, remove the USB flash drive and reboot into your new system!
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] NixOS can be installed on BIOS or UEFI systems.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] The procedure for a UEFI installation is broadly the same as for a BIOS installation.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] The differences are mentioned in the following steps.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] The NixOS manual is available by running `nixos-help` in the command line or from the application menu in the desktop environment.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] To have access to the command line on the graphical images, open Terminal (GNOME) or Konsole (Plasma) from the application menu.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] You are logged-in automatically as `nixos`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] You can use `loadkeys` to switch to your preferred keyboard layout.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] If the text is too small to be legible, try `setfont ter-v32n` to increase the font size.
