[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] When the bootloader lists boot entries, select the serial console boot entry.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] The boot process should have brought up networking (check `ip a`).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Networking is necessary for the installer, since it will download lots of stuff (such as source tarballs or Nixpkgs channel binaries).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] It’s best if you have a DHCP server on your network.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Otherwise configure networking manually using `ip`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] You can configure the network, Wi-Fi included, through NetworkManager.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Using the `nmtui` program, you can do so even in a non-graphical session.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] If you prefer to configure the network manually, disable NetworkManager with `systemctl stop NetworkManager`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] If you would like to continue the installation from a different machine you can use activated SSH daemon.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] You need to copy your ssh key to either `/home/nixos/.ssh/authorized_keys` or `/root/.ssh/authorized_keys` (Tip: For installers with a modifiable filesystem such as the sd-card installer image a key can be manually placed by mounting the image on a different machine).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Alternatively you must set a password for either `root` or `nixos` with `passwd` to be able to login.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] The NixOS installer doesn’t do any partitioning or formatting, so you need to do that yourself.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] The NixOS installer ships with multiple partitioning tools.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] The examples below use `parted`, but also provides `fdisk`, `gdisk`, `cfdisk`, and `cgdisk`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Use the command ‘lsblk’ to find the name of your ‘disk’ device.
