[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] **UEFI systems**Mount the boot file system on `/mnt/boot`, e.g.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] If your machine has a limited amount of memory, you may want to activate swap devices now (`swapon device`).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] The installer (or rather, the build actions that it may spawn) may need quite a bit of RAM, depending on your configuration.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] You now need to create a file `/mnt/etc/nixos/configuration.nix` that specifies the intended configuration of the system.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] This is because NixOS has a *declarative* configuration model: you create or edit a description of the desired configuration of your system, and then NixOS takes care of making it happen.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] The syntax of the NixOS configuration file is described in *Configuration Syntax*, while a list of available configuration options appears in Appendix A.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] If you have network access, you can also install other editors – for instance, you can install Emacs by running `nix-env -f '<nixpkgs>' -iA emacs`.BIOS systemsYou *must* set the option `boot.loader.grub.device` to specify on which disk the GRUB boot loader is to be installed.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Without it, NixOS cannot boot.If there are other operating systems running on the machine before installing NixOS, the `boot.loader.grub.useOSProber` option can be set to `true` to automatically add them to the grub menu.UEFI systemsYou must select a boot-loader, either systemd-boot or GRUB.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] The recommended option is systemd-boot: set the option `boot.loader.systemd-boot.enable` to `true`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] With GRUB, set `boot.loader.grub.useOSProber` to `true`, but this will only detect windows partitions, not other Linux distributions.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] If you dual boot another Linux distribution, use systemd-boot instead.If you need to configure networking for your machine the configuration options are described in *Networking*.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] In particular, while wifi is supported on the installation image, it is not enabled by default in the configuration generated by `nixos-generate-config`.Another critical option is `fileSystems`, specifying the file systems that need to be mounted by NixOS.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] However, you typically don’t need to set it yourself, because `nixos-generate-config` sets it automatically in `/mnt/etc/nixos/hardware-configuration.nix` from your currently mounted file systems.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] (If this happens, boot from the installation media again, mount the target file system on `/mnt`, fix `/mnt/etc/nixos/configuration.nix` and rerun `nixos-install`.) In most cases, `nixos-generate-config` will figure out the required modules.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Do the installation:This will install your system based on the configuration you provided.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] You should now be able to boot into the installed NixOS.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] The GRUB boot menu shows a list of *available configurations* (initially just one).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Every time you change the NixOS configuration (see Changing Configuration), a new item is added to the menu.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] This allows you to easily roll back to a previous configuration if something goes wrong.Use your declared user account to log in.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] If you didn’t declare one, you should still be able to log in using the `root` user.NoteSome graphical display managers such as SDDM do not allow `root` login by default, so you might need to switch to TTY.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Refer to *User Management* for details on declaring user accounts.You may also want to install some software.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] This will be covered in *Package Management*.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] To summarise, Example: Commands for Installing NixOS on `/dev/sda` shows a typical sequence of commands for installing NixOS on an empty hard drive (here `/dev/sda`).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Example: NixOS Configuration shows a corresponding configuration Nix expression.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] The image has to be written verbatim to the USB flash drive for it to be bootable on UEFI and BIOS systems.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Here are the recommended tools to do that.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Etcher is a popular and user-friendly tool.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Download it from balena.io, start the program, select the downloaded NixOS ISO, then select the USB flash drive and flash it.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Etcher reports errors and usage statistics by default, which can be disabled in the settings.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] An alternative is USBImager, which is very simple and does not connect to the internet.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Download the version with write-only (wo) interface for your system.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Start the program, select the image, select the USB flash drive and click “Write”.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Find the corresponding device with `lsblk`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Make sure all partitions on the device are properly unmounted.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Find the corresponding device with `diskutil list`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] After `dd` completes, a GUI dialog “The disk you inserted was not readable by this computer” will pop up, which can be ignored.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Using the ‘raw’ `rdiskX` device instead of `diskX` with dd completes in minutes instead of hours.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Advanced users may wish to install NixOS using an existing PXE or iPXE setup.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] These instructions assume that you have an existing PXE or iPXE infrastructure and want to add the NixOS installer as another option.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] If you’re using plain PXE, configure your boot loader to use the `bzImage` and `initrd` files and have it provide the same kernel command line arguments found in `netboot.ipxe`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] If you’re using iPXE, depending on how your HTTP/FTP/etc. server is configured you may be able to use `netboot.ipxe` unmodified, or you may need to update the paths to the files to match your server’s directory layout.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] In the future we may begin making these files available as build products from hydra at which point we will update this documentation with instructions on how to obtain them either for placing on a dedicated TFTP server or to boot them directly over the internet.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] In some cases, your system might already be booted into/preinstalled with another Linux distribution, and booting NixOS by attaching an installation image is quite a manual process.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] This is particularly useful for (cloud) providers where you can’t boot a custom image, but get some Debian or Ubuntu installation.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] In these cases, it might be easier to use `kexec` to “jump into NixOS” from the running system, which only assumes `bash` and `kexec` to be installed on the machine.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Note that kexec may not work correctly on some hardware, as devices are not fully re-initialized in the process.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] In practice, this however is rarely the case.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] These three files are meant to be copied over to the other already running Linux Distribution.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Note its symlinks pointing elsewhere, so `cd` in, and use `scp * root@$destination` to copy it over, rather than rsync.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Once you finished copying, execute `kexec-boot` *on the destination*, and after some seconds, the machine should be booting into an (ephemeral) NixOS installation medium.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Make sure your `configuration.nix` does still import `netboot-minimal.nix` (or `netboot-base.nix`).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Installing NixOS into a VirtualBox guest is convenient for users who want to try NixOS without installing it on bare metal.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] There are a few modifications you should make in configuration.nix.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Also remove the fsck that runs at startup.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] It will always fail to run, stopping your boot until you press `*`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Shared folders can be given a name and a path in the host system in the VirtualBox settings (Machine / Settings / Shared Folders, then click on the “Add” icon).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Add the following to the `/etc/nixos/configuration.nix` to auto-mount them.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] If you do not add `"nofail"`, the system will not boot properly.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] The folder will be available directly under the root directory.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Because Nix (the package manager) & Nixpkgs (the Nix packages collection) can both be installed on any (most?) Linux distributions, they can be used to install NixOS in various creative ways.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Install NixOS on the same partition (in place!), from your existing non-NixOS Linux distribution using `NIXOS_LUSTRATE`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Install NixOS on your hard drive from the Live CD of any Linux distribution.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Install the NixOS installation tools:You’ll need `nixos-generate-config` and `nixos-install`, but this also makes some man pages and `nixos-enter` available, just in case you want to chroot into your NixOS partition.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] NoteThe following 5 steps are only for installing NixOS to another partition.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] For installing NixOS in place using `NIXOS_LUSTRATE`, skip ahead.Prepare your target partition:At this point it is time to prepare your target partition.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Please refer to the partitioning, file-system creation, and mounting steps of *Installing NixOS*If you’re about to install NixOS in place using `NIXOS_LUSTRATE` there is nothing to do for this step.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Generate your NixOS configuration:You’ll probably want to edit the configuration files.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Refer to the `nixos-generate-config` step in *Installing NixOS* for more information.Consider setting up the NixOS bootloader to give you the ability to boot on your existing Linux partition.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Download/build/install NixOS:WarningOnce you complete this step, you might no longer be able to boot on existing systems without the help of a rescue USB drive or similar.NoteOn some distributions there are separate PATHS for programs intended only for root.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] In order for the installation to succeed, you might have to use `PATH="$PATH:/usr/sbin:/sbin"` in the following command.Again, please refer to the `nixos-install` step in *Installing NixOS* for more information.That should be it for installation to another partition!
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Optionally, you may want to clean up your non-NixOS distribution:If you do not wish to keep the Nix package manager installed either, run something like `sudo rm -rv ~/.nix-* /nix` and remove the line that the Nix installer added to your `~/.profile`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] NoteThe following steps are only for installing NixOS in place using `NIXOS_LUSTRATE`:WarningThe lustrate process will not work if the `boot.initrd.systemd.enable` option is set to `true`, which is now the default.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Setting this to `false` is deprecated and scheduled for removal in NixOS 26.11, along with `NIXOS_LUSTRATE`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Other installation methods, such as the one outlined above, or installing from kexec, are recommended instead.Generate your NixOS configuration:Note that this will place the generated configuration files in `/etc/nixos`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] You’ll probably want to edit the configuration files.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Refer to the `nixos-generate-config` step in *Installing NixOS* for more information.NoteOn UEFI systems, check that your `/etc/nixos/hardware-configuration.nix` did the right thing with the EFI System Partition.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] In NixOS, by default, both systemd-boot and grub expect it to be mounted on `/boot`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] However, the configuration generator bases its `fileSystems` configuration on the current mount points at the time it is run.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Set up the `/etc/NIXOS` and `/etc/NIXOS_LUSTRATE` files:`/etc/NIXOS` officializes that this is now a NixOS partition (the bootup scripts require its presence).`/etc/NIXOS_LUSTRATE` tells the NixOS bootup scripts to move *everything* that’s in the root partition to `/old-root`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] This will move your existing distribution out of the way in the very early stages of the NixOS bootup.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] There are exceptions (we do need to keep NixOS there after all), so the NixOS lustrate process will not touch:The `/nix` directoryThe `/boot` directoryAny file or directory listed in `/etc/NIXOS_LUSTRATE` (one per line)NoteThe act of “lustrating” refers to the wiping of the existing distribution.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Both systemd-boot and grub expect this by default in NixOS, but other distributions vary.WarningOnce you complete this step, your current distribution will no longer be bootable!
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] If you didn’t get all the NixOS configuration right, especially those settings pertaining to boot loading and root partition, NixOS may not be bootable either.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] It’s also worth noting that this whole process can be automated.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] This is especially useful for Cloud VMs, where provider do not provide NixOS.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] For instance, nixos-infect uses the lustrate process to convert Digital Ocean droplets to NixOS from other distributions automatically.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] To install NixOS behind a proxy, do the following before running `nixos-install`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Setup the proxy environment variables in the shell where you are running `nixos-install`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] If you are switching networks with different proxy configurations, use the `specialisation` option in `configuration.nix` to switch proxies at runtime.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Refer to Appendix A for more information.
