[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] If you have a machine that supports hardware virtualisation, you can also test the new configuration in a sandbox by building and running a QEMU *virtual machine* that contains the desired configuration.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] The VM does not have any data from your host system, so your existing user accounts and home directories will not be available unless you have set `mutableUsers = false`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Such port forwardings connect via the VM’s virtual network interface.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] Thus they cannot connect to ports that are only bound to the VM’s loopback interface (`127.0.0.1`), and the VM’s NixOS firewall must be configured to allow these connections.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] The best way to keep your NixOS installation up to date is to use one of the NixOS *channels*.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] A channel is a Nix mechanism for distributing Nix expressions and associated binaries.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] The NixOS channels are updated automatically from NixOS’s Git repository after certain tests have passed and a selection of packages has been built successfully (see `nixos/release-combined.nix` and `nixos/release-small.nix`).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] To see what channels are available, go to https://channels.nixos.org.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] (Note that the URIs of the various channels redirect to a directory that contains the channel’s latest version and includes ISO images and VirtualBox appliances.) Please note that during the release process, channels that are not yet released will be present here as well.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] See the Getting NixOS page https://nixos.org/download/ to find the newest supported stable release.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] When you first install NixOS, you’re automatically subscribed to the NixOS channel that corresponds to your installation source.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] For instance, if you installed from a 26.05 ISO, you will be subscribed to the `nixos-26.05` channel.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] which is equivalent to the more verbose `nix-channel --update nixos; nixos-rebuild switch`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] It is generally safe to switch back and forth between channels.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] The only exception is that a newer NixOS may also have a newer Nix version, which may involve an upgrade of Nix’s database schema.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p01] This cannot be undone easily, so in that case you will not be able to go back to your original channel.
