[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] This chapter describes how to configure various aspects of a NixOS machine through the configuration file `/etc/nixos/configuration.nix`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] As described in *Changing the Configuration*, changes to this file only take effect after you run **nixos-rebuild**.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] The NixOS configuration file `/etc/nixos/configuration.nix` is actually a *Nix expression*, which is the Nix package manager’s purely functional language for describing how to build packages and configurations.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] This means you have all the expressive power of that language at your disposal, including the ability to abstract over common patterns, which is very useful when managing complex systems.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] The syntax and semantics of the Nix language are fully described in the Nix manual, but here we give a short overview of the most important constructs useful in NixOS configuration files.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] The first line (`{ config, pkgs, ... }:`) denotes that this is actually a function that takes at least the two arguments `config` and `pkgs`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] (These are explained later, in chapter *Writing NixOS Modules*) The function returns a *set* of option definitions (`{ ... }`).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] These definitions have the form `name = value`, where `name` is the name of an option and `value` is its value.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] defines a configuration with three option definitions that together enable the Apache HTTP Server with `/webroot` as the document root.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] Sets can be nested, and in fact dots in option names are shorthand for defining a set containing another set.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] For instance, `services.httpd.enable` defines a set named `services` that contains a set named `httpd`, which in turn contains an option definition named `enable` with value `true`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] which may be more convenient if you have lots of option definitions that share the same prefix (such as `services.httpd`).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] NixOS checks your option definitions for correctness.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] Likewise, values in option definitions must have a correct type.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] For instance, `services.httpd.enable` must be a Boolean (`true` or `false`).
