[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] The Nixpkgs configuration for a NixOS system is set by the `nixpkgs.config` option.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] Some packages in Nixpkgs have options to enable or disable optional functionality, or change other aspects of the package.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] Unfortunately, Nixpkgs currently lacks a way to query available package configuration options.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] For example, many packages come with extensions one might add.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] Apart from high-level options, it’s possible to tweak a package in almost arbitrary ways, such as changing or disabling dependencies of a package.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] For instance, the Emacs package in Nixpkgs by default has a dependency on GTK 2.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] The function `override` performs the call to the Nix function that produces Emacs, with the original arguments amended by the set of arguments specified by you.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] So here the function argument `gtk` gets the value `pkgs.gtk3`, causing Emacs to depend on GTK 3.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] Even greater customisation is possible using the function `overrideAttrs`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] While the `override` mechanism above overrides the arguments of a package function, `overrideAttrs` allows changing the *attributes* passed to `mkDerivation`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] This permits changing any aspect of the package, such as the source code.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] Here, `overrideAttrs` takes the Nix derivation specified by `pkgs.emacs` and produces a new derivation in which the original’s `name` and `src` attribute have been replaced by the given values by re-calling `stdenv.mkDerivation`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] The original attributes are accessible via the function argument, which is conventionally named `oldAttrs`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] The overrides shown above are not global.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] They do not affect the original package; other packages in Nixpkgs continue to depend on the original rather than the customised package.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] This means that if another package in your system depends on the original package, you end up with two instances of the package.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] The effect of this definition is essentially equivalent to modifying the `emacs` attribute in the Nixpkgs source tree.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] Any package in Nixpkgs that depends on `emacs` will be passed your customised instance.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] It’s possible that a package you need is not available in NixOS.
