[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] With the command `nix-env`, you can install and uninstall packages from the command line.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] If you invoke this as root, the package is installed in the Nix profile `/nix/var/nix/profiles/default` and visible to all users of the system; otherwise, the package ends up in `/nix/var/nix/profiles/per-user/username/profile` and is not visible to other users.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] The `-A` flag specifies the package by its attribute name; without it, the package is installed by matching against its package name (e.g.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] The latter is slower because it requires matching against all available Nix packages, and is ambiguous if there are multiple matching packages.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] Other packages in the profile are *not* affected; this is the crucial difference with the declarative style of package management, where running `nixos-rebuild switch` causes all packages to be updated to their current versions in the NixOS channel.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] For details, see the nix-env(1) manpage or the Nix manual.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] NixOS supports both declarative and imperative styles of user management.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] In the declarative style, users are specified in `configuration.nix`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] Note that `alice` is a member of the `wheel` and `networkmanager` groups, which allows her to use `sudo` to execute commands as `root` and to configure the network, respectively.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] Also note the SSH public key that allows remote logins with the corresponding private key.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] Users created in this way do not have a password by default, so they cannot log in via mechanisms that require a password.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] However, you can use the `passwd` program to set a password, which is retained across invocations of `nixos-rebuild`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] If you set `users.mutableUsers` to false, then the contents of `/etc/passwd` and `/etc/group` will be congruent to your NixOS configuration.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] For instance, if you remove a user from `users.users` and run nixos-rebuild, the user account will cease to exist.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] Also, imperative commands for managing users and groups, such as useradd, are no longer available.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] Passwords may still be assigned by setting the user’s hashedPassword option.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] A hashed password can be generated using `mkpasswd`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] A user ID (uid) is assigned automatically.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] As with users, the group ID (gid) is optional and will be assigned automatically if it’s missing.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] In the imperative style, users and groups are managed by commands such as `useradd`, `groupmod` and so on.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] To make all nix tools available to this new user use `su - USER` which opens a login shell (==shell that loads the profile) for given user.
