[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] The filesystem will be mounted automatically unless `"noauto"` is present in options.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] `"noauto"` filesystems can be mounted explicitly using `systemctl` e.g.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] Mount points are created automatically if they don’t already exist.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] For `device`, it’s best to use the topology-independent device aliases in `/dev/disk/by-label` and `/dev/disk/by-uuid`, as these don’t change if the topology changes (e.g. if a disk is moved to another IDE controller).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] You can usually omit the file system type (`fsType`), since `mount` can usually detect the type and load the necessary kernel module automatically.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] However, if the file system is needed at early boot (in the initial ramdisk) and is not `ext2`, `ext3` or `ext4`, then it’s best to specify `fsType` to ensure that the kernel module is available.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] System startup will fail if any of the filesystems fails to mount, dropping you to the emergency shell.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] You can make a mount asynchronous and non-critical by adding `options = [ "nofail" ];`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] NixOS supports file systems that are encrypted using *LUKS* (Linux Unified Key Setup).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] The LUKS volume should be automatically picked up by `nixos-generate-config`, but you might want to verify that your `hardware-configuration.nix` looks correct.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] NixOS also supports unlocking your LUKS-Encrypted file system using a FIDO2 compatible token.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] You can also use the FIDO2 passwordless setup, but for security reasons, you might want to enable it only when your device is PIN protected, such as Trezor.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] If systemd stage 1 is enabled, it handles unlocking of LUKS-encrypted volumes during boot.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] The following example enables systemd stage1 and adds support for unlocking the existing LUKS2 volume `root` using any enrolled FIDO2 compatible tokens.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] All tokens that should be used for unlocking the LUKS2-encrypted volume must first be enrolled using systemd-cryptenroll.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] In the following example, a new key slot for the first discovered token is added to the LUKS volume.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] Existing key slots are left intact, unless `--wipe-slot=` is specified.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] It is recommended to add a recovery key that should be stored in a secure physical location and can be entered wherever a password would be entered.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] SSHFS is a FUSE filesystem that allows easy access to directories on a remote machine using the SSH File Transfer Protocol (SFTP).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] It means that if you have SSH access to a machine, no additional setup is needed to mount a directory.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] Mounting non-interactively requires some precautions because `sshfs` will run at boot and under a different user (root).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] For obvious reason, you can’t input a password, so public key authentication using an unencrypted key is needed.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] To keep the key safe, change the ownership to `root:root` and make sure the permissions are `600`: OpenSSH normally refuses to use the key if it’s not well-protected.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] The file system can be configured in NixOS via the usual fileSystems option.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] It’s also possible to change the `ssh` command used by SSHFS to connect to the server.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] The escaping of spaces is needed because every option is written to the `/etc/fstab` file, which is a space-separated table.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] If you’re having a hard time figuring out why mounting is failing, you can add the option `"debug"`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] If the mount point contains special characters it needs to be escaped using `systemd-escape`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] This is due to the way systemd converts paths into unit names.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] NixOS offers a convenient abstraction to create both read-only as well writable overlays.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] If `upperdir` and `workdir` are not null, they will be created before the overlay is mounted.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] To mount an overlay as read-only, you need to provide at least two `lowerdir`s.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] The X Window System (X11) provides the basis of NixOS’ graphical user interface.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] The X server will automatically detect and use the appropriate video driver from a set of X.org drivers (such as `vesa` and `intel`).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] You can also specify a driver manually, e.g.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] to enable X.org’s `xf86-video-r128` driver.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] You also need to enable at least one desktop or window manager.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] Otherwise, you can only log into a plain undecorated `xterm` window.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] NixOS’s default *display manager* (the program that provides a graphical login prompt and manages the X server) is LightDM.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] The X server is started automatically at boot time.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] The x11 login screen can be skipped entirely, automatically logging you into your window manager and desktop environment when you boot your computer.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] This is especially helpful if you have disk encryption enabled.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] Since you already have to provide a password to decrypt your disk, entering a second password to login can be redundant.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p02] To enable auto-login, you need to define your default window manager and desktop environment.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] It is possible to avoid a display manager entirely and starting the X server manually from a virtual terminal.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] then you can start the X server with the `startx` command.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The second option will generate a base `xinitrc` script that will run your window manager and set up the systemd user session.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] or, alternatively, you can write your own from scratch in `~/.xinitrc`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The default and recommended driver for Intel Graphics in X.org is `modesetting` (included in the xorg-server package itself).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] This is a generic driver which uses the kernel mode setting (KMS) mechanism, it supports Glamor (2D graphics acceleration via OpenGL) and is actively maintained, it may perform worse in some cases (like in old chipsets).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] There is a second driver, `intel` (provided by the xf86-video-intel package), specific to older Intel iGPUs from generation 2 to 9.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] It is not recommended by most distributions: it lacks several modern features (for example, it doesn’t support Glamor) and the package hasn’t been officially updated since 2015.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Third generation and older iGPUs (15-20+ years old) are not supported by the `modesetting` driver (X will crash upon startup).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Thus, the `intel` driver is required for these chipsets.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Otherwise, the results vary depending on the hardware, so you may have to try both drivers.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Use the option `services.xserver.videoDrivers` to set one.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The `modesetting` driver doesn’t currently provide a `TearFree` option (this will become available in an upcoming X.org release), So, without using a compositor (for example, see `services.picom.enable`) you will experience screen tearing.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Note that this will likely downgrade the performance compared to `modesetting` or `intel` with DRI 3 (default).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] NVIDIA provides a proprietary driver for its graphics cards that has better 3D performance than the X.org drivers.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] It is not enabled by default because it’s not free software.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] You may need to reboot after enabling this driver to prevent a clash with other kernel modules.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The driver has many options (see Appendix A).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Note: the use of `services.xserver.synaptics` is deprecated since NixOS 17.09.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] GTK themes can be installed either to user profile or system-wide (via `environment.systemPackages`).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] It is possible to install custom XKB keyboard layouts using the option `services.xserver.xkb.extraLayouts`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] As a first example, we are going to create a layout based on the basic US layout, with an additional layer to type some greek symbols by pressing the right-alt key.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The name (after `extraLayouts.`) should match the one given to the `xkb_symbols` block.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Applying this customization requires rebuilding several packages, and a broken XKB file can lead to the X session crashing at login.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Once the configuration is applied, and you did a logout/login cycle, the layout should be ready to use.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] You can try it by e.g. running `setxkbmap us-greek` and then type `<alt>+a` (it may not get applied in your terminal straight away).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] To change the default, the usual `services.xserver.xkb.layout` option can still be used.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] A layout can have several other components besides `xkb_symbols`, for example we will define new keycodes for some multimedia key and bind these to some symbol.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The function `pkgs.writeText <filename> <content>` can be useful if you prefer to keep the layout definitions inside the NixOS configuration.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Unfortunately, the Xorg server does not (currently) support setting a keymap directly but relies instead on XKB rules to select the matching components (keycodes, types, …) of a layout.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] This means that components other than symbols won’t be loaded by default.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] If you are manually starting the X server, you should set the argument `-xkbdir /etc/X11/xkb`, otherwise X won’t find your layout files.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] To learn how to write layouts take a look at the XKB documentation .
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] More example layouts can also be found here .
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] While X11 (see *X Window System*) is still the primary display technology on NixOS, Wayland support is steadily improving.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Where X11 separates the X Server and the window manager, on Wayland those are combined: a Wayland Compositor is like an X11 window manager, but also embeds the Wayland ‘Server’ functionality.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] This installs the sway compositor along with some essential utilities.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Now you can start sway from the TTY console.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] If you are using a wlroots-based compositor, like sway, and want to be able to share your screen, make sure to configure Pipewire using `services.pipewire.enable` and related options.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] For more helpful tips and tricks, see the wiki page about Sway.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] NixOS provides various APIs that benefit from GPU hardware acceleration, such as VA-API and VDPAU for video playback; OpenGL and Vulkan for 3D graphics; and OpenCL for general-purpose computing.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] This chapter describes how to set up GPU hardware acceleration (as far as this is not done automatically) and how to verify that hardware acceleration is indeed used.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Most of the aforementioned APIs are agnostic with regards to which display server is used.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Consequently, these instructions should apply both to the X Window System and Wayland compositors.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] It is used by various applications such as Blender and Darktable to accelerate certain operations.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] OpenCL applications load drivers through the *Installable Client Driver* (ICD) mechanism.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] In this mechanism, an ICD file specifies the path to the OpenCL driver for a particular GPU family.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] In NixOS, there are two ways to make ICD files visible to the ICD loader.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The first is through the `OCL_ICD_VENDORS` environment variable.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] This variable can contain a directory which is scanned by the ICL loader for ICD files.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The second mechanism is to add the OpenCL driver package to `hardware.graphics.extraPackages`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] This links the ICD file under `/run/opengl-driver`, where it will be visible to the ICD loader.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The proper installation of OpenCL drivers can be verified through the `clinfo` command of the clinfo package.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Modern AMD Graphics Core Next (GCN) GPUs are supported through the rocmPackages.clr.icd package.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Intel Gen12 and later GPUs are supported by the Intel NEO OpenCL runtime that is provided by the `intel-compute-runtime` package.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The previous generations (8,9 and 11), have been moved to the `intel-compute-runtime-legacy1` package.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The proprietary Intel OpenCL runtime, in the `intel-ocl` package, is an alternative for Gen7 GPUs.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Both `intel-compute-runtime` packages, as well as the `intel-ocl` package can be added to `hardware.graphics.extraPackages` to enable OpenCL support.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Vulkan is a graphics and compute API for GPUs.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] It is used directly by games or indirectly though compatibility layers like DXVK.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] By default, if `hardware.graphics.enable` is enabled, Mesa is installed and provides Vulkan for supported hardware.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Similar to OpenCL, Vulkan drivers are loaded through the *Installable Client Driver* (ICD) mechanism.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] ICD files for Vulkan are JSON files that specify the path to the driver library and the supported Vulkan version.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] All successfully loaded drivers are exposed to the application as different GPUs.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] In NixOS, there are two ways to make ICD files visible to Vulkan applications: an environment variable and a module option.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The way to do this is to add the Vulkan driver package to `hardware.graphics.extraPackages`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The proper installation of Vulkan drivers can be verified through the `vulkaninfo` command of the vulkan-tools package.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] A simple graphical application that uses Vulkan is `vkcube` from the vulkan-tools package.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Modern AMD Graphics Core Next (GCN) GPUs are supported through the RADV driver, which is part of mesa.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] VA-API (Video Acceleration API) is an open-source library and API specification, which provides access to graphics hardware acceleration capabilities for video processing.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The version in nixpkgs is built to search the opengl driver path, so drivers can be installed in `hardware.graphics.extraPackages`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Except where noted explicitly, it should not be necessary to adjust user permissions to use these acceleration APIs.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] In the default configuration, GPU devices have world-read/write permissions (`/dev/dri/renderD*`) or are tagged as `uaccess` (`/dev/dri/card*`).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The access control lists of devices with the `uaccess` tag will be updated automatically when a user logs in through `systemd-logind`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] If you disabled (this functionality of) `systemd-logind`, you may need to add the user to the `video` group and log in again.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The *Installable Client Driver* (ICD) mechanism used by OpenCL and Vulkan loads runtimes into its address space using `dlopen`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Mixing an ICD loader mechanism and runtimes from different version of nixpkgs may not work.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] For example, if the ICD loader uses an older version of glibc than the runtime, the runtime may not be loadable due to missing symbols.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Unfortunately, the loader will generally be quiet about such issues.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] If you suspect that you are running into library version mismatches between an ICL loader and a runtime, you could run an application with the `LD_DEBUG` variable set to get more diagnostic information.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] For example, OpenCL can be tested with `LD_DEBUG=files clinfo`, which should report missing symbols.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Some Xfce programs are not installed automatically.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] To install them manually (system wide), put them into your `environment.systemPackages`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Thunar (the Xfce file manager) is automatically enabled when Xfce is enabled.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] To enable Thunar without enabling Xfce, use the configuration option `programs.thunar.enable` instead of adding `pkgs.thunar` to `environment.systemPackages`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] If you’d like to add extra plugins to Thunar, add them to `programs.thunar.plugins`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] You shouldn’t just add them to `environment.systemPackages`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Even after enabling udisks2, volume management might not work.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Thunar and/or the desktop takes time to show up.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Thunar will spit out this kind of message on start (look at `journalctl --user -b`).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] This is caused by some needed GNOME services not running.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] This is all fixed by enabling “Launch GNOME services on startup” in the Advanced tab of the Session and Startup settings panel.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Alternatively, you can run this command to do the same thing.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] It is necessary to log out and log in again for this to take effect.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] This section describes how to configure networking components on your NixOS machine.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] To facilitate network configuration, some desktop environments use NetworkManager.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] some desktop managers (e.g., GNOME) enable NetworkManager automatically for you.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] NetworkManager is controlled using either `nmcli` or `nmtui` (curses-based terminal user interface).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] See their manual pages for details on their usage.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Some desktop environments (GNOME, KDE) have their own configuration tools for NetworkManager.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] On XFCE, there is no configuration tool for NetworkManager by default: by enabling `programs.nm-applet.enable`, the graphical applet will be installed and will launch automatically when the graphical session is started.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] `networking.networkmanager` and `networking.wireless` (WPA Supplicant) can be used together if desired.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Refer to the option description for the exact syntax and references to external documentation.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] By default, root logins using a password are disallowed.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] They can be disabled entirely by setting `services.openssh.settings.PermitRootLogin` to `"no"`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] By default, NixOS uses DHCP (specifically, `dhcpcd`) to automatically configure network interfaces.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Addresses and routes for statically configured interfaces and the default gateway are set up by systemd services named `network-addresses-<interface>.service`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The name servers configuration, instead, is performed by `network-local-commands.service` using resolvconf.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Set it to the empty string (`""`) to allow the DHCP server to provide the host name.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Stateless address autoconfiguration is used to automatically assign IPv6 addresses to all interfaces, and Privacy Extensions (RFC 4941) are enabled by default.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] You can adjust the default for this by setting `networking.tempAddresses`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] This option may be overridden on a per-interface basis by `networking.interfaces.<name>.tempAddress`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] As with IPv4 networking interfaces are automatically configured via DHCPv6.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] See the section called “IPv4 Configuration” for similar examples and additional information.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] NixOS has a simple stateful firewall that blocks incoming connections and other unexpected packets.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The firewall applies to both IPv4 and IPv6 traffic.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Note that TCP port 22 (ssh) is opened automatically if the SSH daemon is enabled (`services.openssh.enable = true`).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] UDP ports can be opened through `networking.firewall.allowedUDPPorts`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Similarly, UDP port ranges can be opened through `networking.firewall.allowedUDPPortRanges`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] For a desktop installation using NetworkManager (e.g., GNOME or KDE), you should make sure the user is in the `networkmanager` group and you can just configure wireless networks from the Settings app.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] It is also possible to declare (some) wireless networks from the NixOS configuration with `networking.networkmanager.ensureProfiles.profiles`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] By default, wpa_supplicant will manage the first wireless interface that becomes available.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] It is however recommended to set the desired interface name with `networking.wireless.interfaces`, as it is more reliable.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] results in `wpa_supplicant-wlan0.service` and `wpa_supplicant-wlan1.service`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] If the network is using WPA2, the pre-shared key (PSK) can be also specified with the `pskRaw` option as 64 hexadecimal digits.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] This is useful to both obfuscate passwords and make the connection slightly faster, as the key doesn’t need to be derived every time.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Other wpa_supplicant configuration can be set using the `extraConfig` option, either globally or per-network.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The generated wpa_supplicant configuration file is linked to `/etc/wpa_supplicant/nixos.conf` for easier inspection.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Be aware that in the previous examples the keys would be written to the Nix store in plain text and readable to every local user.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] It is recommended to specify secrets (PSKs, passwords, etc.) in a safe way using `networking.wireless.secretsFile` and the `ext:` syntax.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The secrets file should be owned and placed in a location accessible (only) by the `wpa_supplicant` user.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Only certain fields support the `ext:` syntax, for example `psk`, `sae_password` and `password`, but not `ssid`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] It can be useful to add a new network without rebuilding the NixOS configuration, particularly if you don’t yet have Internet access.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Setting `networking.wireless.userControlled` to `true` will allow users of the `wpa_supplicant` group to configure wpa_supplicant imperatively.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Note that these changes will be lost when wpa_supplicant is restarted.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] To make them persistent, the option `networking.wireless.allowAuxiliaryImperativeNetworks` can be set, which allows to use the `save` command in `wpa_cli`, or even directly editing the file `/etc/wpa_supplicant/imperative.conf`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] if `networking.wireless.interfaces` has been set.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] For examples and a list of available options, see the wpa_supplicant.conf(5) man page.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] By default, security hardening measures that limit access to files, devices and network capabilities are applied to the wpa_supplicant daemon.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Certificates and other files supplied here need to be readable by the `wpa_supplicant` user; it is therefore recommended to store them in the `/etc/wpa_supplicant` directory.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] This setting also applies to networks configured from NetworkManager, unless the WiFi backend in use is not wpa_supplicant.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] You can use `networking.localCommands` to specify shell commands to be run after the network interfaces have been created, but not necessarily fully configured.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] This is useful for doing network configuration not covered by the existing NixOS modules.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The commands should ideally be idempotent, so it’s recommended to perform cleanups of the state you create (e.g. virtual interfaces), or at least make sure possible failures are handled.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] NixOS uses the udev predictable naming scheme to assign names to network interfaces.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] This means that by default cards are not given the traditional names like `eth0` or `eth1`, whose order can change unpredictably across reboots.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Instead, relying on physical locations and firmware information, the scheme produces names like `ens1`, `enp2s0`, etc.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] These names are predictable but less memorable and not necessarily stable: for example installing new hardware or changing firmware settings can result in a name change.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] If this is undesirable, for example if you have a single ethernet card, you can revert to the traditional scheme by setting `networking.usePredictableInterfaceNames` to `false`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] In case there are multiple interfaces of the same type, it’s better to assign custom names based on the device hardware address.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Note that links are directly read by udev, *not networkd*, and will work even if networkd is disabled.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The rule must be installed in the initrd using `boot.initrd.services.udev.rules`, not the usual `services.udev.extraRules` option.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] This is to avoid race conditions with other programs controlling the interface.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] You can override the Linux kernel and associated packages using the option `boot.kernelPackages`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Note that this not only replaces the kernel, but also packages that are specific to the kernel version, such as the NVIDIA video drivers.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] This ensures that driver packages are consistent with the kernel.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] While `pkgs.linuxKernel.packages` contains all available kernel packages, you may want to use one of the unversioned `pkgs.linuxPackages_*` aliases such as `pkgs.linuxPackages_latest`, that are kept up to date with new versions.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Please note that the current convention in NixOS is to only keep actively maintained kernel versions on both unstable and the currently supported stable release(s) of NixOS.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] This means that a non-longterm kernel will be removed after it’s abandoned by the kernel developers, even on stable NixOS versions.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] If you pin your kernel onto a non-longterm version, expect your evaluation to fail as soon as the version is out of maintenance.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] A kernel will be removed from nixpkgs when the first batch of stable kernels *after* the final release is published.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] E.g. when 6.15.11 is the final release of the 6.15 series and is released together with 6.16.3 and 6.12.43, it will be removed on the release of 6.16.4 and 6.12.44.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Custom kernel variants such as linux-hardened are also affected by this.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Longterm versions of kernels will be removed before the next stable NixOS that will exceed the maintenance period of the kernel version.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The default Linux kernel configuration should be fine for most users.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] If you want to change the kernel configuration, you can use the `packageOverrides` feature (see the section called “Customising Packages”).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] `extraConfig` takes a list of Linux kernel configuration options, one per line.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The name of the option should not include the prefix `CONFIG_`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The option value is typically `y`, `n` or `m` (to build something as a kernel module).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Kernel modules for hardware devices are generally loaded automatically by `udev`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] You can force a module to be loaded via `boot.kernelModules`, e.g.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] This causes the specified modules and their dependencies to be added to the initial ramdisk.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Kernel runtime parameters can be set through `boot.kernel.sysctl`, e.g.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] sets the kernel’s TCP keepalive time to 120 seconds.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] To see the available parameters, run `sysctl -a`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Please refer to the Nixpkgs manual for the various ways of building a custom kernel.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The Linux kernel does not have Rust language support enabled by default.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] For kernel versions 6.7 or newer, experimental Rust support can be enabled.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] This section was moved to the Nixpkgs manual.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] It’s a common issue that the latest stable version of ZFS doesn’t support the latest available Linux kernel.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] It is recommended to use the latest available LTS that’s compatible with ZFS.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Usually this is the default kernel provided by nixpkgs (i.e.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Subversion is a centralized version-control system.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] It can use a variety of protocols for communication between client and server.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] This section focuses on configuring a web-based server on top of the Apache HTTP server, which uses WebDAV/DeltaV for communication.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] For more information on the general setup, please refer to the the appropriate section of the Subversion book.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The key `"svn"` is just a symbolic name identifying the virtual host.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The `"/svn"` in `locations."/svn".extraConfig` is the path underneath which the repositories will be served.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] This page explains how to set up the Subversion configuration itself.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The Subversion repositories will be accessible as `http://HOSTNAME/svn/REPO_NAME`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] GNOME provides a simple, yet full-featured desktop environment with a focus on productivity.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Its Mutter compositor supports both Wayland and X server, and the GNOME Shell user interface is fully customizable by extensions.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] All of the core apps, optional apps, games, and core developer tools from GNOME are available.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] While it is not strictly necessary to use GDM as the display manager with GNOME, it is recommended, as some features such as screen lock might not work without it.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The default applications used in NixOS are very minimal, inspired by the defaults used in gnome-build-meta.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] If you’d only like to omit a subset of the core utilities, you can use `environment.gnome.excludePackages`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Note that this mechanism can only exclude core utilities, games and core developer tools.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] It is also possible to disable many of the core services.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Note, however, that doing so is not supported and might break some applications.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Notably, GNOME Music cannot work without TinySPARQL.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] GNOME Flashback provides a desktop environment based on the classic GNOME 2 architecture.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] It is also possible to create custom sessions that replace Metacity with a different window manager using `services.desktopManager.gnome.flashback.customSessions`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Icon themes and GTK themes don’t require any special option to install in NixOS.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] You can add them to `environment.systemPackages` and switch to them with GNOME Tweaks.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Most Shell extensions are packaged under the `gnomeExtensions` attribute.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Some packages that include Shell extensions, like `gpaste`, don’t have their extension decoupled under this attribute.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Unfortunately, we lack a way for these to be managed in a completely declarative way.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] So you have to enable them manually with an Extensions application.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] It is possible to use a GSettings override for this on `org.gnome.shell.enabled-extensions`, but that will only influence the default value.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Majority of software building on the GNOME platform use GLib’s GSettings system to manage runtime configuration.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] For our purposes, the system consists of XML schemas describing the individual configuration options, stored in the package, and a settings backend, where the values of the settings are stored.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] On NixOS, like on most Linux distributions, dconf database is used as the backend.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] GSettings vendor overrides can be used to adjust the default values for settings of the GNOME desktop and apps by replacing the default values specified in the XML schemas.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Using overrides will allow you to pre-seed user settings before you even start the session.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Overrides really only change the default values for GSettings keys so if you or an application changes the setting value, the value set by the override will be ignored.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Until NixOS’s dconf module implements changing values, you will either need to keep that in mind and clear the setting from the backend using `dconf reset` command when that happens, or use the module from home-manager.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] You can override the default GSettings values using the `services.desktopManager.gnome.extraGSettingsOverrides` option.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Take note that whatever packages you want to override GSettings for, you need to add them to `services.desktopManager.gnome.extraGSettingsOverridePackages`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] You can use `dconf-editor` tool to explore which GSettings you can set.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Yes you can, and any other display-manager in NixOS.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] However, it doesn’t work correctly for the Wayland session of GNOME Shell yet, and won’t be able to lock your screen.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Pantheon is the desktop environment created for the elementary OS distribution.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] It is written from scratch in Vala, utilizing GNOME technologies with GTK and Granite.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] All of Pantheon is working in NixOS and the applications should be available, aside from a few exceptions.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] This automatically enables LightDM and Pantheon’s LightDM greeter.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] but please be aware using Pantheon without LightDM as a display manager will break screenlocking from the UI.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The NixOS module for Pantheon installs all of Pantheon’s default applications.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] You can also use `environment.pantheon.excludePackages` to remove any other app (like `elementary-mail`).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Wingpanel and Switchboard work differently than they do in other distributions, as far as using plugins.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] You cannot install a plugin globally (like with `environment.systemPackages`) to start using it.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] to configure the programs with plugs or indicators.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] The difference in NixOS is both these programs are patched to load plugins from a directory that is the value of an environment variable.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] please note that, like how the NixOS options describe these as extra plugins, this would only add to the default plugins included with the programs.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] this could be most useful for testing a particular plug-in in isolation.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Open Switchboard and go to: Administration → About → Restore Default Settings → Restore Settings.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] This will reset any dconf settings to their Pantheon defaults.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] Note this could reset certain GNOME specific preferences if that desktop was used prior.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] This is a known issue and there is no known workaround.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] AppCenter is available and the Flatpak backend should work so you can install some Flatpak applications using it.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] However, due to missing appstream metadata, the Packagekit backend does not function currently.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p03] If you are using Pantheon, AppCenter should be installed by default if you have Flatpak support enabled.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] The **Xen Project Hypervisor** is an open-source type-1 virtual machine manager which allows multiple virtual machines, known as *domains*, to run concurrently with the host on the physical machine.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] This is unlike a typical type-2 hypervisor, such as QEMU, where the virtual machines run as applications on top of the host.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] NixOS runs as the privileged *Domain 0*, and can paravirtualise (PV Mode) or fully virtualise (HVM Mode) unprivileged domains (`domUs`).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] All Xen Security Advisories are patched within hours of release, and generally reach the binary cache channels within a couple of days.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Xen may be used as a Domain 0 since NixOS 24.11, using the `virtualisation.xen.enable` option.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] There are various hardware and software requirements to running a Xen Domain 0; the module is configured to prevent running Xen on a NixOS system that does not meet the software requirements.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] (i.e. a NixOS system that uses the legacy, scripted initial ramdisk.) The module does not yet check if the hardware requirements are met: please manually ensure that the target machine supports SLAT and IOMMU, the latter being required only for non-PV domains to be virtualised.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] The boot menu on a Xen-enabled NixOS system will show duplicate entries for each generation: one boots a normal NixOS system, and the other boots into the Xen Project Hypervisor.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] The `systemd-boot` and Limine bootloaders are the only supported boot methods at this time.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Xen may be managed through various frontend configuration systems.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] `libxenlight` is one such configuration system, and is built into all Xen systems.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] The `xl` command is the primary command-line interface to `libxenlight`, and is capable of managing a NixOS Domain 0.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Known generically as guests, unprivileged domains running NixOS may import the `xen-domU.nix` profile in their configurations to automatically enable various recommended optimisations which are relevant for unprivileged domains.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] tpm2-totp attests the trustworthiness of a device against a human using time-based one-time passwords.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] This module uses a `tpm2-totp` configuration to display a TOTP at boot using Plymouth.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Switch to the new configuration before proceeding to the next step.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Generate a new TOTP secret and save the secret in your chosen authenticator app.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] See `man tpm2-totp` for commands and configuration examples.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] More information, including security considerations, can be found in the `README.md` in the tpm2-totp repository.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Be sure to select the tag for the version of `tpm2-totp` you have installed.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Reboot and you should see the TOTP appear on the Plymouth boot screen.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] The TOTP should match the code displayed in your authenticator app (or the code immediately before/after).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] NixOS has support for several bootloader backends by default: systemd-boot, grub, uboot, etc.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] The built-in bootloader backend support is generic and supports most use cases.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Some users may prefer to create advanced workflows around managing the bootloader and bootable entries.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] You can replace the built-in bootloader support with your own tooling using the “external” bootloader option.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Imagine you have created a new package called FooBoot.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] FooBoot provides a program at `${pkgs.fooboot}/bin/fooboot-install` which takes the system closure’s path as its only argument and configures the system’s bootloader.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Bootloaders should use RFC-0125’s Bootspec format and synthesis tools to identify the key properties for bootable system generations.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Clevis is a framework for automated decryption of resources.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Clevis allows for secure unattended disk decryption during boot, using decryption policies that must be satisfied for the data to decrypt.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] The first step is to embed your secret in a JWE file.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] JWE files have to be created through the clevis command line.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Using Shamir’s Secret Sharing (sss), secrets are pinned using a combination of the two preceding policies.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] For more complete documentation on how to generate a secret with clevis, see the clevis documentation.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Then, specify the device you want to decrypt using a given clevis secret.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Clevis will automatically try to decrypt the device at boot and will fallback to interactive unlocking if the decryption policy is not fulfilled.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Only `bcachefs`, `zfs` and `luks` encrypted devices are supported at this time.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Garage is an open-source, self-hostable S3 store, simpler than MinIO, for geodistributed stores.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] The server setup can be automated using services.garage.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] A client configured to your local Garage instance is available in the global environment as `garage-manage`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Garage has two types of upgrades: patch-level upgrades and minor/major version upgrades.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] In all cases, you should read the changelog and ideally test the upgrade on a staging cluster.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Checking the health of your cluster can be achieved using `garage-manage repair`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Here are some baseline instructions to handle advanced upgrades in Garage, when in doubt, please refer to upstream instructions.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Your upgraded cluster should be in a working state, re-enable API and web access.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] As stated in the previous paragraph, we must provide a clean upgrade-path for Garage since it cannot move more than one major version forward on a single upgrade.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] This chapter adds some notes how Garage updates should be rolled out in the future.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] This is inspired from how Nextcloud does it.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] While patch-level updates are no problem and can be done directly in the package-expression (and should be backported to supported stable branches after that), major-releases should be added in a new attribute (e.g.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Garage `v3.0.0` should be available in `nixpkgs` as `pkgs.garage_3`).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] To provide simple upgrade paths it’s generally useful to backport those as well to stable branches.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] As long as the package-default isn’t altered, this won’t break existing setups.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] After that, the versioning-warning in the `garage`-module should be updated to make sure that the package-option selects the latest version on fresh setups.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] If major-releases will be abandoned by upstream, we should check first if those are needed in NixOS for a safe upgrade-path before removing those.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Ideally we should make sure that it’s possible to jump two NixOS versions forward: i.e. the warnings and the logic in the module should guard a user to upgrade from a Garage on e.g.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] YouTrack is a browser-based bug tracker, issue tracking system and project management software.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] YouTrack exposes a web GUI installer on first login.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] You can find this token in the log of the `youtrack` service.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Starting with YouTrack 2023.1, JetBrains no longer distributes it as as JAR.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] The new distribution with the JetBrains Launcher as a ZIP changed the basic data structure and also some configuration parameters.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Check out https://www.jetbrains.com/help/youtrack/server/YouTrack-Java-Start-Parameters.html for more information on the new configuration options.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] When upgrading to YouTrack 2023.1 or higher, a migration script will move the old state directory to `/var/lib/youtrack/2022_3` as a backup.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Change the data directory location to `/var/lib/youtrack/data/`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] The other paths should already be right.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] If you migrate a larger YouTrack instance, it might be useful to set `-Dexodus.entityStore.refactoring.forceAll=true` in `services.youtrack.generalParameters` for the first startup of YouTrack 2023.x.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] An image board engine dedicated for small and medium communities.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] By default the module will execute Szurubooru server only, the web client only contains static files that can be reached via a reverse proxy.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] The preferred method to run this service is behind a reverse proxy not to expose an open port.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] You can find all of the options in the default config file available here.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] A free and open source manga reader server that runs extensions built for Tachiyomi.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] It runs in the systemd service named `suwayomi-server` in the data directory `/var/lib/suwayomi-server`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] strfry is a relay for the nostr protocol.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] It runs in the systemd service named `strfry`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Plausible is a privacy-friendly alternative to Google analytics.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] At first, a secret key is needed to be generated.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] The Pi-hole suite provides a web GUI for controlling and monitoring pihole-FTL.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] The dashboard can be configured using `services.pihole-ftl.settings`, in particular the `webserver` subsection.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] pict-rs is a a simple image hosting service.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] this will start the http server on port 8080 by default.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] OpenCloud is an open-source, modern file-sync and sharing platform.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] It is a fork of oCIS, a ground-up rewrite of the well-known PHP-based NextCloud server.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] The service can be configured using a combination of `services.opencloud.settings`, `services.opencloud.environment` and `services.opencloud.environmentFile`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] OpenCloud is configured using a combination of YAML and environment variables.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] The full documentation can be found at OpenCloud Admin Docs.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Please note that current NixOS module for OpenCloud is configured to run in `fullstack` mode, which starts all the services for OpenCloud in a single instance, in so called supervised mode.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] This will start multiple OpenCloud services and listen on multiple other ports.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Nextcloud is an open-source, self-hostable cloud platform.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] The server setup can be automated using services.nextcloud.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] A desktop client is packaged at `pkgs.nextcloud-client`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] The current default by NixOS is `nextcloud33` which is also the latest major version available.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Nextcloud is a PHP-based application which requires an HTTP server (`services.nextcloud` and optionally supports `services.nginx`).
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] For the database, you can set `services.nextcloud.config.dbtype` to either `sqlite` (the default), `mysql`, or `pgsql`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] The simplest is `sqlite`, which will be automatically created and managed by the application.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] For the last two, you can easily create a local database by setting `services.nextcloud.database.createLocally` to `true`, Nextcloud will automatically be configured to connect to it through socket.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] The `hostName` option is used internally to configure an HTTP server using `PHP-FPM` and `nginx`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] The `config` attribute set is used by the imperative installer and all values are written to an additional file to ensure that changes can be applied by changing the module’s options.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] In case the application serves multiple domains (those are checked with `$_SERVER['HTTP_HOST']`) it’s needed to add them to `services.nextcloud.settings.trusted_domains`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Auto updates for Nextcloud apps can be enabled using `services.nextcloud.autoUpdateApps`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] The management command `occ` can be invoked by using the `nextcloud-occ` wrapper that’s globally available on a system with Nextcloud enabled.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] It requires elevated permissions to become the `nextcloud` user.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Given the way the privilege escalation is implemented, parameters passed via the environment to Nextcloud are currently ignored, except for `OC_PASS` and `NC_PASS`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] When Polkit is enabled, the command being executed by `nextcloud-occ` might be logged into the system’s journal.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Be careful to not leak secrets that way!
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Please note that the options required are subject to change.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Please make sure to read the release notes when upgrading.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] By default, `nginx` is used as reverse-proxy for `nextcloud`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] `httpd` by explicitly disabling `nginx` using `services.nginx.enable` and fixing the settings `listen.owner` & `listen.group` in the `phpfpm` pool `nextcloud`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Nextcloud apps are installed statefully through the web interface.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Some apps may require extra PHP extensions to be installed.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] This can be configured with the `services.nextcloud.phpExtraExtensions` setting.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Alternatively, extra apps can also be declared with the `services.nextcloud.extraApps` setting.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Keep in mind that this is essentially a mirror of the apps from the appstore, but managed in nixpkgs.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] This is by no means a curated list of apps that receive special testing on each update.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] If you want automatic updates it is recommended that you use web interface to install apps.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] If you want to view logs in the admin panel, set `services.nextcloud.settings.log_type` to “file”.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] If you prefer logs in the journal, disable the logreader application to shut up the “info”.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] We can’t really do that by default since whether apps are enabled/disabled is part of the application’s state and tracked inside the database.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] As stated in the previous paragraph, we must provide a clean upgrade-path for Nextcloud since it cannot move more than one major version forward on a single upgrade.
