[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Matomo is a real-time web analytics application.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] This module configures php-fpm as backend for Matomo, optionally configuring an nginx vhost as well.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] An automatic setup is not supported by Matomo, so you need to configure Matomo itself in the browser-based Matomo setup.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] You also need to configure a MariaDB or MySQL database and -user for Matomo yourself, and enter those credentials in your browser.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Then fill in `matomo` as database user and database name, and leave the password field blank.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] This authentication works by allowing only the `matomo` unix user to authenticate as the `matomo` database user (without needing a password), but no other users.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] For more information on passwordless login, see https://mariadb.com/kb/en/mariadb/unix_socket-authentication-plugin/.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Of course, you can use password based authentication as well, e.g. when the database is not on the same host.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] This module comes with the systemd service `matomo-archive-processing.service` and a timer that automatically triggers archive processing every hour.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] This means that you can safely disable browser triggers for Matomo archiving at `Administration > System > General Settings`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] You only need to take backups of your MySQL database and the `/var/lib/matomo/config/config.ini.php` file.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Use a user in the `matomo` group or root to access the file.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] For more information, see https://matomo.org/faq/how-to-install/faq_138/.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] You can use other web servers by forwarding calls for `index.php` and `piwik.php` to the `services.phpfpm.pools.<name>.socket` fastcgi unix socket.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] You can use the nginx configuration in the module code as a reference to what else should be configured.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Lemmy is a federated alternative to reddit in rust.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] This will start the backend on port 8536 and the frontend on port 1234.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] It will expose your instance with a caddy reverse proxy to the hostname you’ve provided.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Postgres will be initialized on that same instance automatically.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] On first connection you will be asked to define an admin user.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Keycloak is an open source identity and access management server with support for OpenID Connect, OAUTH 2.0 and SAML 2.0.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] An administrative user with the username `admin` is automatically created in the `master` realm.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Its initial password can be configured by setting `services.keycloak.initialAdminPassword` and defaults to `changeme`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] The password is not stored safely and should be changed immediately in the admin panel.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Refer to the Keycloak Server Administration Guide for information on how to administer your Keycloak instance.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Keycloak can be used with either PostgreSQL, MariaDB or MySQL.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Which one is used can be configured in `services.keycloak.database.type`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] The selected database will automatically be enabled and a database and role created unless `services.keycloak.database.host` is changed from its default of `localhost` or `services.keycloak.database.createLocally` is set to `false`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] External database access can also be configured by setting `services.keycloak.database.host`, `services.keycloak.database.name`, `services.keycloak.database.username`, `services.keycloak.database.useSSL` and `services.keycloak.database.caCert` as appropriate.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Note that you need to manually create the database and allow the configured database user full access to it.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] `services.keycloak.database.passwordFile` must be set to the path to a file containing the password used to log in to the database.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] If `services.keycloak.database.host` and `services.keycloak.database.createLocally` are kept at their defaults, the database role `keycloak` with that password is provisioned on the local database instance.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] The path should be provided as a string, not a Nix path, since Nix paths are copied into the world readable Nix store.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] For PostgreSQL, Keycloak can connect via Unix socket using peer authentication, avoiding the need for a database password.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Unix socket authentication is only supported for PostgreSQL.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] The hostname is used to build the public URL used as base for all frontend requests and must be configured through `services.keycloak.settings.hostname`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] If you’re migrating an old Wildfly based Keycloak instance and want to keep compatibility with your current clients, you’ll likely want to set `services.keycloak.settings.http-relative-path` to `/auth`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] See the option description for more details.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] `services.keycloak.settings.hostname-backchannel-dynamic` Keycloak has the capability to offer a separate URL for backchannel requests, enabling internal communication while maintaining the use of a public URL for frontchannel requests.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Moreover, the backchannel is dynamically resolved based on incoming headers endpoint.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] For more information on hostname configuration, see the Hostname section of the Keycloak Server Installation and Configuration Guide.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] By default, Keycloak won’t accept unsecured HTTP connections originating from outside its local network.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] HTTPS support requires a TLS/SSL certificate and a private key, both PEM formatted.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Their paths should be set through `services.keycloak.sslCertificate` and `services.keycloak.sslCertificateKey`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] The paths should be provided as a strings, not a Nix paths, since Nix paths are copied into the world readable Nix store.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] You can package custom themes and make them visible to Keycloak through `services.keycloak.themes`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] See the Themes section of the Keycloak Server Development Guide and the description of the aforementioned NixOS option for more information.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Keycloak server configuration parameters can be set in `services.keycloak.settings`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] These correspond directly to options in `conf/keycloak.conf`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Some of the most important parameters are documented as suboptions, the rest can be found in the All configuration section of the Keycloak Server Installation and Configuration Guide.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Options containing secret data should be set to an attribute set containing the attribute `_secret` - a string pointing to a file containing the value the option should be set to.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] See the description of `services.keycloak.settings` for an example.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] With Jitsi Meet on NixOS you can quickly configure a complete, private, self-hosted video conferencing solution.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] Jitsi Meet depends on the Prosody XMPP server only for message passing from the web browser while the default Prosody configuration is intended for use with standalone XMPP clients and XMPP federation.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p04] If you only use Prosody as a backend for Jitsi Meet it is therefore recommended to also enable `services.jitsi-meet.prosody.lockdown` option to disable unnecessary Prosody features such as federation or the file proxy.
