[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p05] These can be modified by setting `services.akkoma.frontends`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p05] The following example overrides the primary frontend’s default configuration using a custom derivation.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p05] Akkoma comes with a number of modules to police federation with other ActivityPub instances.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p05] The most valuable for typical users is the `:mrf_simple` module which allows limiting federation based on instance hostnames.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p05] This configuration snippet provides an example on how these can be used.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p05] Choosing an adequate federation policy is not trivial and entails finding a balance between connectivity to the rest of the fediverse and providing a pleasant experience to the users of an instance.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p05] This example strips GPS and location metadata from uploads, deduplicates them and anonymises the the file name.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p05] Pleroma instances can be migrated to Akkoma either by copying the database and upload data or by pointing Akkoma to the existing data.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p05] The necessary database migrations are run automatically during startup of the service.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p05] The configuration has to be copy‐edited manually.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p05] Depending on the size of the database, the initial migration may take a long time and exceed the startup timeout of the system manager.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p05] Copying the Pleroma data instead of re‐using it in place may permit easier reversion to Pleroma, but allows the two data sets to diverge.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p05] After the data has been copied, enable the Akkoma service and verify that the migration has been successful.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p05] To re‐use the Pleroma data in place, disable Pleroma and enable Akkoma, pointing it to the Pleroma database and upload directory.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p05] Please keep in mind that after the Akkoma service has been started, any migrations applied by Akkoma have to be rolled back before the database can be used again with Pleroma.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p05] This can be achieved through `pleroma_ctl ecto.rollback`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p05] Refer to the Ecto SQL documentation for details.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p05] Confinement of services is not generally supported in NixOS and therefore disabled by default.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p05] Use `services.systemd.akkoma.confinement.packages` to make packages available in the chroot.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p05] `services.systemd.akkoma.serviceConfig.BindPaths` and `services.systemd.akkoma.serviceConfig.BindReadOnlyPaths` permit access to outside paths through bind mounts.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p05] Refer to `BindPaths=` of systemd.exec(5) for details.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p05] Being an Elixir application, Akkoma can be deployed in a distributed fashion.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p05] This requires setting `services.akkoma.dist.address` and `services.akkoma.dist.cookie`.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p05] The specifics depend strongly on the deployment environment.
[src:nixos/manual-nixos-p05] For more information please check the relevant Erlang documentation.
